<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Ohio Workers</h2>

<h3>My Ohio income is around $28,000. How much state income tax should I expect?</h3>
<p>At $28,000 annual income, you would owe Ohio tax only on the portion above the $26,050 threshold -- that's $1,950 taxable at 2.765%, which equals approximately $54 for the full year, or about $4.50 per bi-weekly paycheck. This is one of the lowest state income tax burdens in the country for lower-middle income workers. The $0 rate below $26,050 effectively makes Ohio a no-income-tax state for lower earners.</p>

<h3>I work in Columbus and live in a suburb. Do I pay Columbus city tax?</h3>
<p>Yes. Columbus's 2.5% municipal income tax applies to wages earned within Columbus city limits, regardless of where you live. If your employer is located in Columbus, they should withhold Columbus city tax. If you also live in a suburb with its own local tax, you may receive a credit for taxes paid to Columbus (many suburban municipalities provide a 100% credit for taxes paid to the city where you work). Contact both your employer's payroll department and your municipality's tax authority to understand your exact obligation. The city tax line on your stub should show Columbus's 2.5%.</p>

<h3>Ohio eliminated several income tax brackets recently. Will rates keep changing?</h3>
<p>Ohio has been actively reducing income taxes as part of a decade-long initiative. The legislature has reduced the number of brackets and the top rate multiple times since 2005. While future changes are possible -- and the Republican-controlled legislature has expressed interest in further reductions -- no committed future changes were enacted as of early 2024. When generating stubs for future dates, verify current Ohio tax rates with the Ohio Department of Taxation website, as the rates in this calculator reflect 2024 information.</p>

<h3>Does Ohio have paid family leave or disability insurance that deducts from wages?</h3>
<p>No. Ohio does not have state-mandated paid family leave or a state disability insurance program funded through employee payroll deductions. Ohio workers who need short-term disability coverage must purchase private insurance or rely on employer-provided plans. There is no "Ohio SDI" or "Ohio PFL" line on your pay stub. This contrasts with neighboring Pennsylvania (no SDI either), but both differ from states like California, New York, and New Jersey which do have employee-funded state programs. The absence of these deductions means slightly higher take-home pay for Ohio workers compared to states with these programs.</p>

<h3>I'm a gig worker in Cleveland delivering for multiple apps. How do I generate an Ohio pay stub?</h3>
<p>Calculate your total gross earnings for each pay period across all platforms (DoorDash, Uber Eats, Instacart, etc.) and enter that as gross pay. As an independent contractor, no state or federal taxes are withheld from your gig payments -- you will need to make quarterly estimated tax payments to both the IRS and Ohio Department of Taxation. The pay stub shows what withholding would be on an equivalent employment basis, which helps you estimate your quarterly obligations. If you deliver in Cleveland, you may also owe Cleveland's 2.5% municipal income tax on that self-employment income, though the mechanics differ from employee withholding -- consult a local tax professional. See our <a href="/self-employed-pay-stub-generator">self-employed pay stub generator</a> for more on documenting gig income.</p>

